Pass an accessor so the query is rebuilt when its inputs change.

```ts
// Svelte
const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
);

// Solid
const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId() }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
}));
```

In Svelte, dispose the subscription with the component; in Solid, keep the input reactive.

Define the employee table first, then reference it by name. Make the manager relation optional:

```ts
import { schema as s } from "jazz-tools";

const schema = {
  employees: s.table({
    name: s.string(),
    managerId: s.ref("employees").optional(),
  }),
};

export const app = s.defineApp(schema);
```

Use `managerId: null` when an employee has no manager.

Use a numeric column for an event timestamp, a bytes column for an eagerly loaded small fingerprint, and a ref column for the project relation:

```ts
const schema = {
  projects: s.table({ name: s.string() }),
  events: s.table({
    occurredAt: s.number(),
    fingerprint: s.bytes(),
    projectId: s.ref("projects"),
  }),
};
```

Store the timestamp in a documented unit such as Unix milliseconds. `s.bytes()` is inline row data; use a file/blob column only for larger or separately loaded data.

Use the exact conventional tables and keep access rooted at `uploads`:

```ts
const schema = {
  file_parts: s.table({ data: s.bytes() }),
  files: s.table({
    name: s.string().optional(),
    mimeType: s.string(),
    partIds: s.array(s.ref("file_parts")),
    partSizes: s.array(s.int()),
  }),
  uploads: s.table({
    owner_id: s.string(),
    label: s.string(),
    fileId: s.ref("files"),
  }),
};
```

Allow the owner to read/write/delete `uploads`. Allow the helper’s pre-parent inserts for `files` and `file_parts` only as narrowly as the threat model permits, preferably through a trusted backend. Grant file reads/deletes via `allowedTo.readReferencing`/`deleteReferencing` from `uploads.fileId`, and part reads/deletes via the corresponding `files.partIds` relationship. Do not make file reads public; file and part updates are normally unnecessary because files are write-once.

Upload with an edge write tier and only report success after the parent reference also settles at edge:

```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });
const upload = await db.insert(app.uploads, {
  owner_id: session.user_id,
  label: "Attachment",
  fileId: file.id,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

For a download, request the edge tier so incomplete local chunks can be fetched:

```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof IncompleteFileDataError) {
    // Surface unavailable/corrupt attachment; inspect reason for missing-part or size mismatch.
  } else if (error instanceof FileNotFoundError) {
    // The file row is not visible to this user or no longer exists.
  } else throw error;
}
```

A stronger read tier can wait for remote data, but cannot repair a genuinely missing or corrupt upstream part.

Load the parent and referenced file while inherited permissions still exist, then delete dependencies in order: every `file_parts` row, the `files` row, and finally the `uploads` parent.

```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}
db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```

Do not delete the parent first: removing its relationship can revoke inherited delete access to the file and chunks. Handle missing file rows explicitly and add application cleanup if parent creation fails after the file has been uploaded.

Use `counter` for the integer and `g-set` for tags:

```ts
const schema = {
  stats: s.table({ count: s.int().default(0).merge("counter") }),
  posts: s.table({ tags: s.array(s.string()).default([]).merge("g-set") }),
};
```

Counter writes remain snapshots (`count: row.count + delta`); concurrent deltas are summed from their common ancestor. A base of 10 with concurrent values 12 and 9 converges to 11. `g-set` converges concurrent tag arrays to a deduplicated union, including ancestor tags. It does not prohibit later sequential replacement, so use append-only operation rows if removals must be impossible or every intent needs identity.

Render an immediate local subscription, but track confirmation per write:

```ts
const result = useSubscription(query, {
  localUpdates: "immediate",
  propagation: "full",
});

async function save(patch: Patch) {
  setSyncState("pending");
  try {
    const write = db.update(app.documents, id, patch);
    await write.wait({ tier: "edge" });
    setSyncState("edge-confirmed");
  } catch (error) {
    setSyncState({ kind: "rejected-or-reconnect-failed", error });
  }
}
```

The rendered row may be optimistic while the state is `pending`; never infer edge confirmation from the render. Keep an `onMutationError` listener for un-awaited or restart-surviving rejections, and expose reconnect failure separately while edge waits remain pending offline. Use `disconnect()`/`reconnect()` only on the owning unscoped database, then retry the edge wait after reconnection.

Use a fresh in-memory Jazz server and two memory-backed clients. Insert rows with a stable application key, await each writer’s `.wait({ tier: "edge" })`, then use `vi.waitFor` until the second client observes all rows. Sort both the observed keys and expected keys before asserting, so query order is irrelevant. Shut down both clients and the server in teardown.

```ts
it("syncs several rows deterministically", async () => {
  const server = await startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true });
  const alice = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, adminSecret: server.adminSecret, driver: { type: "memory" } });
  const bob = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, adminSecret: server.adminSecret, driver: { type: "memory" } });
  try {
    const expected = ["row-a", "row-b", "row-c"];
    for (const key of expected) await alice.insert(app.rows, { key }).wait({ tier: "edge" });

    await vi.waitFor(async () => {
      const rows = await bob.all(app.rows, { tier: "edge" });
      expect(rows.map((row) => row.key).sort()).toEqual([...expected].sort());
    });
  } finally {
    await alice.shutdown();
    await bob.shutdown();
    await server.stop();
  }
});
```

Use `createPolicyTestApp` with an ownership policy, create separate Alice and Bob sessions, and insert Alice’s row through Alice so creator attribution is recorded. Assert Bob’s denied read resolves to an empty result, while Bob’s update and delete are rejected. Also assert Alice can still read and modify the row.

```ts
it("denies Bob reads and writes to Alice's row", async () => {
  const testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
  try {
    const alice = testApp.as({ user_id: "alice", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
    const bob = testApp.as({ user_id: "bob", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
    const row = alice.insert(app.rows, { title: "Alice only" }).value;

    await expect(bob.all(app.rows.where({ id: row.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);
    bob.expectDenied((db) => db.update(app.rows, row.id, { title: "Bob changed" }));
    bob.expectDenied((db) => db.delete(app.rows, row.id));

    await expect(alice.one(app.rows.where({ id: row.id }))).resolves.toMatchObject({ title: "Alice only" });
    alice.expectAllowed((db) => db.update(app.rows, row.id, { title: "Alice changed" }));
  } finally {
    await testApp.shutdown();
  }
});
```
